[[File:Hiroshige Bizen Tanokuchi.jpg|thumb|[[Utagawa Hiroshige]]]]
'''Yuga Shrine Hongū''' ({{lang|ja|由加神社本宮}}) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en}} located on Mount Yuga in the Kojima area of southern {{ill|Kurashiki|en}}, {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|en}}, Japan. It is a {{ill|Tandoku Shrine|en|単立神社}} unaffiliated with the {{ill|Association of Shinto Shrines|en}}. Its modern status under the shrine ranking system is a former {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|en|県社}}.

== Overview ==
Mount Yuga has been a center of {{ill|Iwakura faith|en|磐座信仰}} since ancient times. In 733 CE, the monk {{ill|Gyōki|en}} enshrined an {{ill|Eleven-faced Kannon|en|十一面観音}} statue here, establishing a religious complex that merged Shinto and Buddhism under the name '''{{nihongo|Yuga Daigongen|瑜伽大権現}}''' (Yuga Great Incarnation). According to the history of {{ill|Kumano Shrine (Kurashiki)|en}}, five disciples of {{ill|En no Gyōja|en}}, a prominent ascetic, brought Kumano deities from {{ill|Kii Province|en}} and established Kumano Shrine in the northern foothills of Mount Yuga. They later founded Nachi Shrine on Mount Yuga as one of the "New Kumano Three Mountains."

From the mid-{{ill|Edo period|en}}, the shrine became a place of worship for the {{ill|Ikeda clan (Okayama)|en}}, rulers of {{ill|Bizen Province|en}}. The Ikeda clan sponsored the construction of the shrine’s buildings and nearby {{ill|Rendaiji (Kurashiki)|en}}.

The shrine is located in a bustling {{ill|Monzen town|en|門前町}}, with numerous souvenir shops and food stalls. During the New Year period, the shrine attracts many visitors. A specialty of Mount Yuga is the locally famous "ankoro mochi" (sweet red bean rice cakes).

In the {{ill|Meiji period|en}}, the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) policy split Yuga Shrine from Rendaiji Temple. Yuga Shrine now has 52 branch shrines across western Japan.

After {{ill|World War II|en}}, the shrine and temple informally resumed cooperation, with temple monks conducting prayers at the shrine. However, Yuga Shrine formally resumed independent religious activities in 1997, leading to a dispute with Rendaiji over property and operations.

In the Edo period, a practice known as "dual pilgrimage" emerged, encouraging worshippers to visit both {{ill|Yuga Daigongen|en}} and {{ill|Konpira Daigongen|en}} in {{ill|Sanuki Province|en}}.

== Deities ==
The shrine’s deities include:
* {{ill|Hikosashiri no Mikoto|en}}
* {{ill|Kami-naobi no Kami|en}}
* {{ill|Gongen|en}} (Manifestation: {{ill|Amitābha|en}}, {{ill|Medicine Buddha|en}})
* {{ill|Te-Oki-Ho-Nori no Mikoto|en}}
* {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi no Kami|en}}
* {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|en}}
* {{ill|Uka-no-Mitama no Kami|en}}
* {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|en}}
* {{ill|Watatsumi|en}}

== Cultural Properties ==
* **Main Hall** – Built in the early Edo period, it is designated as an {{ill|Important Cultural Property of Okayama Prefecture|en|岡山県指定重要文化財}} (1961).<ref name=岡山県文>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pref.okayama.jp/cgi-bin/bunka/culture/controller/client/resultDetail.cgi?id=174 |title=Main Hall of Yuga Shrine |publisher=Okayama Prefecture |accessdate=2018-06-24}}</ref>

== Access ==
* **By Car:** About 15 minutes from [[Seto-Chuo Expressway]]'s {{ill|Mizushima Interchange|en}}.
* **By Taxi:** About 15 minutes from {{ill|Kojima Station|en}} on the {{ill|Seto-Ohashi Line|en}}.
* **By Bus:** A limited {{ill|Shimoden Bus|en}} service runs from Kojima Station to Yuga Shrine (twice daily). However, buses do not operate on weekends, holidays, or during the New Year period.

