'''Yuga Shrine Hongū''' ({{lang|ja|由加神社本宮}}) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en}} located on [[Yuga Mountain]] in the Kojima area of southern {{ill|Kurashiki|en|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|en}}, Japan. It is a {{ill|Standalone Shrine|ja|単立神社|12=draft|12=draft}} unaffiliated with the {{ill|Association of Shinto Shrines|en}}. Its modern status under the shrine ranking system is a former {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
Mount Yuga has been a center of {{ill|Iwakura rock|lt=Iwakura faith|ja|磐座信仰|12=draft|12=draft}} since ancient times. In 733 CE, the monk {{ill|Gyōki|en}} enshrined an {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|lt=Eleven-faced Kannon|ja|十一面観音|12=draft|12=draft}} statue here, establishing a religious complex that merged Shinto and Buddhism under the name '''{{nihongo|{{ill|Yuga Daigongen|ja|瑜伽大権現|en|12=draft|12=draft}}|瑜伽大権現}}''' (Yuga Great Incarnation). According to the history of {{ill|Kumano Shrine (Kurashiki)|lt=Kumano Shrine|ja|熊野神社 (倉敷市林)|12=draft|12=draft}}, five disciples of {{ill|En no Gyōja|en}}, a prominent ascetic, brought Kumano deities from {{ill|Kii Province|en|12=draft|12=draft}} and established Kumano Shrine in the northern foothills of Mount Yuga. They later founded Nachi Shrine on Mount Yuga as one of the "New Kumano Three Mountains."

From the mid-{{ill|Edo period|en}}, the shrine became a place of worship for the {{ill|Ikeda clan (Okayama)|lt=Ikeda clan|ja|池田氏|en|12=draft|12=draft}}, rulers of {{ill|Bizen Province|en}}. The Ikeda clan sponsored the construction of the shrine’s buildings and nearby {{ill|Rendaiji (Kurashiki)|lt=Rendaiji|ja|蓮台寺_(倉敷市)|en|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The shrine is located in a bustling {{ill|Monzen town|ja|門前町|12=draft|12=draft}}, with numerous souvenir shops and food stalls. During the New Year period, the shrine attracts many visitors. A specialty of Mount Yuga is the locally famous "ankoro mochi" (sweet red bean rice cakes).

In the {{ill|Meiji period|en}}, the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en|12=draft|12=draft}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) policy split Yuga Shrine from Rendaiji Temple. Yuga Shrine now has 52 branch shrines across western Japan.

After {{ill|World War II|en}}, the shrine and temple informally resumed cooperation, with temple monks conducting prayers at the shrine. However, Yuga Shrine formally resumed independent religious activities in 1997, leading to a dispute with Rendaiji over property and operations.

In the Edo period, a practice known as "dual pilgrimage" emerged, encouraging worshippers to visit both {{ill|Yuga Daigongen|ja|瑜伽大権現|en|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Konpira Gongen|en}} in {{ill|Sanuki Province|ja|讃岐国|en|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines Hikosa no Oshinomikoto, Kamunaobi-no-Kami, Daigongen (Honji Buddha: {{ill|Amitābha|ja|阿弥陀如来|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来|1=Bhaisajyaguru|lt=Yakushi Nyorai (Me)dicine Buddha|12=draft|12=draft}}), and others, including:
* {{ill|Hikosa-no-Oshinomikoto|ja|彦狭知命|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Kamunaobi-no-Kami|ja|神直日神|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Yuga Daigongen|ja|瑜伽大権現|en|12=draft|12=draft}} (associated Buddhas: {{ill|Amitābha|ja|阿弥陀如来|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来|1=Bhaisajyaguru|lt=Yakushi Nyorai (Me)dicine Buddha|12=draft|12=draft}})
* {{ill|Teokihobufu no Mikoto|ja|手置帆負命|1=Sanuki Inbe clan|lt=Teokihobufu no Mikoto|2=ja|3=讃岐忌部氏|12=draft|12=draft}} 
* {{ill|Amenominakanushi|ja|天之御中主神|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素盞鳴命|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Ukanomitama|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Kami|ja|倉稲魂命|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Watatsumi|lt=Watatsumi-no-Mikoto|ja|大綿津見命|12=draft|12=draft}}

*

== Cultural Properties ==
* '''main hall''' – Built in the early Edo period, it is designated as an {{ill|Important Cultural Property of Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県指定重要文化財|12=draft|12=draft}} (1961).<ref name=岡山県文>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pref.okayama.jp/cgi-bin/bunka/culture/controller/client/resultDetail.cgi?id=174 |title=main hall of Yuga Shrine |publisher=Okayama Prefecture |accessdate=2018-06-24}}</ref>

== Access ==
* '''By Car:''' About 15 minutes from [[Seto-Chuo Expressway]]'s {{ill|Mizushima Interchange|en}}.
* '''By Taxi:''' About 15 minutes from {{ill|Kojima Station|en|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Seto-Ohashi Line|en}}.
* '''By Bus:''' A limited {{ill|Shimoden Bus|en|12=draft|12=draft}} service runs from Kojima Station to Yuga Shrine (twice daily). However, buses do not operate on weekends, holidays, or during the New Year period.

