From the mid-{{ill|Edo period|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, the shrine became a place of worship for the [[:en:Ikeda clan|Ikeda clan]], rulers of {{ill|Bizen Province|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bizen Province|qq=}}. The Ikeda clan sponsored the construction of the shrine’s buildings and nearby {{ill|Rendaiji (Kurashiki)|lt=Rendaiji|ja|蓮台寺_(倉敷市)|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rendaiji (Kurashiki)|qq=}}.

The shrine is located in a bustling {{ill|Monzen-machi|ja|門前町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monzen-machi|qq=}}, with numerous souvenir shops and food stalls. During the New Year period, the shrine attracts many visitors. A specialty of Mount Yuga is the locally famous "ankoro mochi" (sweet red bean rice cakes).

In the {{ill|Meiji period|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji period|qq=}}, the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) policy split Yuga Shrine from Rendaiji Temple. Yuga Shrine now has 52 branch shrines across western Japan.

After {{ill|World War II|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/World War II|qq=}}, the shrine and temple informally resumed cooperation, with temple monks conducting prayers at the shrine. However, Yuga Shrine formally resumed independent religious activities in 1997, leading to a dispute with Rendaiji over property and operations.

In the Edo period, a practice known as "dual pilgrimage" emerged, encouraging worshippers to visit both {{ill|Yuga Daigongen|ja|瑜伽大権現|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yuga Daigongen|qq=}} and {{ill|Konpira Gongen|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konpira Gongen|qq=}} in [[:en:Sanuki Province|Sanuki Province]].
== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines Hikosa no Oshinomikoto, Kamunaobi-no-Kami, Daigongen (Honji Buddha: [[:en:Amitābha|Amitābha]], [[:en:Bhaisajyaguru|Yakushi Nyorai Medicine Buddha]]), and others, including:
* {{ill|Hikosachi no Mikoto|lt=Hikosachi no Mikoto|lt=Hikosa-no-Oshinomikoto|ja|彦狭知命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hikosa-no-Oshinomikoto|qq=}}
* {{ill|Kamuna'obi|ja|神直日神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamunaobi-no-Kami|qq=}}
* {{ill|Yuga Daigongen|ja|瑜伽大権現|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yuga Daigongen|qq=}} (associated Buddhas: [[:en:Amitābha|Amitābha]], [[:en:Bhaisajyaguru|Yakushi Nyorai Medicine Buddha]])
* {{ill|Teokihobufu no Mikoto|ja|手置帆負命|1=Sanuki Inbe clan|lt=Teokihobufu no Mikoto|2=ja|3=讃岐忌部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Teokihobufu no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanuki Inbe clan|qq=}} 
* [[:en:Ame-no-Minakanushi|Ame-no-Minakanushi]]
* {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素盞鳴命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スサノオ}}
* {{ill|Ukanomitama|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Kami|ja|倉稲魂命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ukanomitama|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ウカノミタマ}}
* {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara no Michizane|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}
* {{ill|Watatsumi|lt=Watatsumi-no-Mikoto|ja|大綿津見命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watatsumi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}

*

== Cultural Properties ==
* '''main hall''' – Built in the early Edo period, it is designated as an {{ill|Important Cultural Property of Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県指定重要文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Cultural Property of Okayama Prefecture|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (1961).<ref name=岡山県文>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pref.okayama.jp/cgi-bin/bunka/culture/controller/client/resultDetail.cgi?id=174 |title=main hall of Yuga Shrine |publisher=Okayama Prefecture |accessdate=2018-06-24}}</ref>

== Access ==
* '''By Car:''' About 15 minutes from [[Seto-Chuo Expressway]]'s {{ill|Mizushima Interchange|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mizushima Interchange|qq=}}.
* '''By Taxi:''' About 15 minutes from {{ill|Kojima Station|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojima Station|qq=}} on the {{ill|Seto-Ohashi Line|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seto-Ohashi Line|qq=}}.
* '''By Bus:''' A limited {{ill|Shimoden Bus|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimoden Bus|qq=}} service runs from Kojima Station to Yuga Shrine (twice daily). However, buses do not operate on weekends, holidays, or during the New Year period.

